26 Committee concerning:
27 (i) A comprehensive array of career advancement guidelines,
28 including standards for each occupation in a profession and concrete steps and
29 accomplishments needed to progress to a greater skilled occupation in a given field;
30 (ii) Credentials to be issued at each stage of advancement and
31 criteria necessary to be awarded a particular credential; and

SENATE BILL 311 17
1 (iii) Necessary adjustments to ensure that the State’s CTE system
2 remains globally competitive and administered according to best global practices.
3 (2) In making recommendations under this subsection, the Advisory
4 Committee shall strive to create a comprehensive, unified system of career progression
5 that:
6 (i) Is attuned to the State’s workforce needs;
7 (ii) Features integration among as many industries as possible;
8 (iii) Features performance assessments administered by industry
9 practitioners whenever possible;
10 (iv) Allows a student trained in one career to seamlessly transfer the
11 student’s skills and education to a new career in a different field;
12 (v) Seeks to incorporate as much education in a job setting as is
13 practicable;
14 (vi) Incorporates professional workplace soft skills, including
15 interpersonal and communication skills, time management, business etiquette, and use of
16 common business tools; and
17 (vii) Incorporates education in high school, community college, and
18 other postsecondary occupation programs into a seamless whole that will provide students
19 with credentials at various points that build on previous credentials.
20 (g) The terms, meeting times, procedures, and policies guiding removal of
21 members for the Advisory Committee shall be determined by the CTE Committee.]
22 21–210.
23 (A) (1) FOR EACH OCCUPATION ON THE LIST DEVELOPED UNDER §
24 21–209(H) OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE CTE COMMITTEE SHALL DEVELOP, IN
25 COLLABORATION WITH THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD,
26 COMPREHENSIVE, PUBLICLY ACCESSIBLE CAREER PATHWAY INFORMATION.
27 (2) THE CAREER PATHWAY INFORMATION SHALL INCLUDE
28 INFORMATION ON:
29 (I) SKILLS, KNOWLEDGE, COMPETENCIES, EXPERIENCE, OR
30 CREDENTIAL STANDARDS FOR EACH OCCUPATION;

18 SENATE BILL 311
1 (II) CONCRETE STEPS TO OBTAIN THE SKILLS, COMPETENCIES,
2 EXPERIENCES, OR CREDENTIALS NECESSARY TO ADVANCE ON A CAREER PATHWAY
3 OR TO HIGHER–PAYING ROLES IN A PROFESSION;
4 (III) CREDENTIALS TO BE ISSUED AT EACH STAGE OF CAREER
5 PATHWAY ADVANCEMENT; AND
6 (IV) NECESSARY CRITERIA TO BE AWARDED A CREDENTIAL.
7 (3) THE CAREER PATHWAY INFORMATION SHALL BE ADOPTED BY THE
8 GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD.
9 (B) ALL STATE AGENCIES AND RELEVANT WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT AND
10 EDUCATION PROGRAMS SHALL USE THE LIST OF OCCUPATIONS DEVELOPED UNDER
11 § 21–209(H) OF THIS SUBTITLE AND CAREER PATHWAY INFORMATION DEVELOPED
12 UNDER THIS SECTION AS A GUIDELINE FOR CURRICULUM ALIGNMENT,
13 CREDENTIALING, AND CAREER ADVANCEMENT.
14 21–211.
15 IN MAKING THE RECOMMENDATIONS REQUIRED UNDER § 21–209(H) OF THIS
16 SUBTITLE REGARDING ADJUSTMENTS TO THE STATE’S CTE SYSTEM, THE CTE
17 COMMITTEE SHALL STRIVE TO CREATE A COMPREHENSIVE, UNIFIED SYSTEM OF
18 CAREER PROGRESSION THAT:
19 (1) IS ATTUNED TO THE STATE’S WORKFORCE NEEDS;
20 (2) FEATURES INTEGRATION AMONG AS MANY INDUSTRIES AS
21 POSSIBLE;
22 (3) FEATURES PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENTS ADMINISTERED BY
23 INDUSTRY PRACTITIONERS WHENEVER POSSIBLE;
24 (4) ALLOWS A STUDENT TRAINED IN ONE CAREER TO SEAMLESSLY
25 TRANSFER THE STUDENT’S SKILLS AND EDUCATION TO A NEW CAREER IN A
26 DIFFERENT FIELD;
27 (5) INCORPORATES PROFESSIONAL WORKPLACE SOFT SKILLS,
28 INCLUDING INTERPERSONAL AND COMMUNICATION SKILLS, TIME MANAGEMENT,
29 BUSINESS ETIQUETTE, AND USE OF COMMON BUSINESS TOOLS; AND
30 (6) INCORPORATES EDUCATION IN HIGH SCHOOL, COMMUNITY
31 COLLEGE, AND OTHER POSTSECONDARY OCCUPATIONAL TRAINING PROGRAMS

SENATE BILL 311 19
1 INTO A UNIFIED SYSTEM THAT WILL PROVIDE STUDENTS WITH CREDENTIALS AT
2 VARIOUS POINTS THAT BUILD ON PREVIOUS CREDENTIALS.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
4 (a) Notwithstanding the provisions of §§ 5–206 and 5–411 § 5–411 of the
5 Education Article:
6 (1), the State Department of Education shall suspend operation of the
7 Expert Review Team Program during the 2026–2027 school year; and
8 (2) the funding allocated for the Expert Review Team Program in the fiscal
9 year 2027 operating budget shall be transferred to the Academic Excellence Fund
10 established under § 6–1105 of the Education Article.
11 (b) Notwithstanding any limitations in Chapter 4 of the Acts of 2026, in the fiscal
12 year 2027 operating budget:
13 (1) $3,334,574 of the appropriation for the Expert Review Team Program
14 under Aid to Education (R00A02) may be used for the Judith P. Hoyer Early Childhood
15 Education Enhancement Program established under § 5–230 of the Education Article; and
16 (2) $3,334,574 of the fiscal year 2027 General Fund appropriation for the
17 Judith P. Hoyer Early Childhood Education Enhancement Program under Aid to Education
18 (R00A02) may be transferred to the Academic Excellence Fund established under § 6–1105
19 of the Education Article.
20 (b) (c) On or before November 1, 2026, the State Department of Education and the
21 Accountability and Implementation Board jointly shall submit a report to the Governor
22 and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the Senate Budget and
23 Taxation Committee, the Senate Education, Energy, and the Environment Committee, the
24 House Appropriations Committee, and the House Ways and Means Committee on plans for
25 future implementation of the Expert Review Team Program under § 5–411 of the Education
26 Article.
27 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
28 (a) The Accountability and Implementation Board and State Department of
29 Education shall identify a methodology for counting students from low–income households
30 to calculate the Compensatory Education formula under § 5–222 of the Education Article.
31 (b) The Accountability and Implementation Board and the State Department of
32 Education shall engage in a collaborative and transparent process for identifying the
33 method for counting students from low–income households under subsection (a) of this
34 section, including consultation with the Department of Budget and Management and the
35 Department of Legislative Services.

20 SENATE BILL 311
1 (c) On or before December 31, 2026, the The Accountability and Implementation
2 Board and the State Department of Education jointly shall submit a report the following
3 reports on their findings and recommendations regarding the methodology for counting
4 students from low–income households under this section to the Governor and, in accordance
5 with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly:
6 (1) on or before December 31, 2026, an interim report; and
7 (2) on or before September 30, 2027, a final report.
8 SECTION 2. 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
9 July 1, 2026.
Approved:
